How much more does each friend have to pay now that Brad isn't participating?<n>Output: Start by finding the total that is left, $1700 car price - $500 earned at car wash = $<<1700-500=1200>>1200 remaining.<n>So the six friends should pay $1200 / 6 people = $<<1200/6=200>>200 each.<n>Since Brad is not joining, then the 5 friends have to split Brad's share which is $200/5 = $<<200/5=40>>40 each.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input: Harper needs to buy teacher appreciation gifts for her children’s teachers.  Her son has 3 different teachers and her daughter has 4.  If she spent $70 on gifts, how much did each gift cost?<n>Output: Her son has 3 teachers and her daughter has 4, so together they have 3+4 = <<3+4=7>>7 teachers<n>Harper has already spent $70 on 7 gifts, so she spent $70/7 = $<<70/7=10>>10 per gift<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input:She had a knack for entertaining, everybody told he she had a what? Choices:  A: fun B: talent C: learn about D: intelligence E: recognize<n>Output:		She has a knack for entertain. So the option is A<n><n><div class="d-flex flex-column align-items-center"><n><p class="mt-2"><n>The given puzzle is:<n><n>Input: She had a knack for entering, everyone told her she had a what?<n>Choices: A: fun B: a talent C: learn about <img class="mr-2"><n>D: ingenuity E: recognize<n></p><n><div class="btn-toolbar mb-2 mb-md-0"><n><div class="ms-auto"><n>  <a href="#" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm" onclick="javascript:toggleAnswer('question_5031199574326','answer_5031031322866'); return false;">Show Answer</a><n></div><n></div>   <n></div><n><n><!--Answers--><n><n><style type="text/css"><n>  div.d-flex.flex-column.align-items-center {<n>  background-color: #383838;<n>  overflow: auto;<n>}<n>div.d-flex.btn-toolbar {<n>  background-image: url("{{URL}}/front/img/solutionButton.png");<n>}<n><n>.d-flex.ml-5.gallery.gallery-thumbnails {<n>  min-height: 250px;<n>}<n>.d-flex.ms-auto {<n>  margin-left: -9%;<n>}<n>.dish2 {<n>  display: block;<n>  width: 50%;<n>  padding: 20px;<n>  border: 2px dashed rgba(255, 255, 0, 0.5);<n>  background-color:#FFC;<n>  transition: ease.2s;<n>  cursor: pointer;<n>}<n><n>.answered {<n>  display: none;<n>}<n></style><n><n><script type="text/javascript"><n>var answer_5031963927750347 = false;<n>function toggleAnswer(questionId, answerId) {<n>  answer_5030
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20. If Hurley is 14 years old, what are their combined ages 40 years from now?<n>Output: If Hurley is 14 years old, and the difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20, Richard is 20+14 = <<20+14=34>>34<n>Forty years from now, Hurley will be 14+40 = <<14+40=54>>54 years old.<n>Richard will be 40+34 = <<40+34=74>>74 years forty years from now.<n>Their combined ages forty years from now will be 74+54 = <<74+54=128>>128 years<n>So the final answer is 128<n><n>Input: Pablo’s mother agrees to pay him one cent for every page he reads. He plans to save the money for some candy. Pablo always checks out books that are exactly 150 pages. After reading his books, he went to the store and bought $15 worth of candy and had $3 leftover. How many books did Pablo read?<n>Output: He gets $1.5 per book because.01 x 150 = <<.01*150=1.5>>1.5<n>He earned $18 because 15 + 3 = <<15+3=18>>18<n>He read 12 books because 18 / 1.5 = <<18/1.5=12>>12<n>So the final answer is 12<n><n>Input: A group of six friends planned to buy a car. The cost of the car is $1700 and they plan to share the cost equally. They had a car wash to help raise funds, which would be taken out of the total cost. The remaining cost would be split between the six friends. At the car wash, they earn $500. However, Brad decided not to join in the purchase of the car. How much more does each friend have to pay now that Brad isn't participating?<n>Output: Start by finding the total that is left, $1700 car price - $500 earned at car wash = $<<1700-500=1200>>1200 remaining.<n>So the six friends should pay $1200 / 6 people = $<<1200/6=200>>200 each.<n>Since Brad is not joining, then the 5 friends have to split Brad's share which is $200/5 = $<<200/5=40>>40 each.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input: Harper needs to buy teacher appreciation gifts for her children’s teachers.  Her son has 3 different teachers and her daughter has 4.  If she spent $70 on gifts, how much did each gift cost?<n>Output: Her son has 3 teachers and her daughter has 4, so together they have 3+4 = <<3+4=7>>7 teachers<n>Harper has already spent $70 on 7 gifts, so she spent $70/7 = $<<70/7=10>>10 per gift<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input:Dave put his beer where he could get to it, but it would be off the floor.  Where did he put it? Choices:  A: refrigerator B: closet C: can D: shelf E: soccer game<n>Output:		<<A=fridge, B=closet, C=can, D=shelf, E=soccer game>> E = soccer game The answer is E, the soccer game<n><n>Input: In order to win the spelling bee, you must know how to spell every English word. There are 10,949 English words in Collins English Dictionary.  The contestant correctly spelling a word in the bee can only be used once. If, one day, you need to spell one of the 10,950 words, where should you look to spell it? Choices: A: In the dictionary C: On the Internet B: In the dictionary’s index E: In the dictionary<n>Output: <<A:dictionary, C:Internet, B:dictionary's index, E:dictionary>> The answer A is the dictionary<n><n>Input: What word is made by rearranging these 4 letters: BACD? Choices: The choices include <<A=back, C=bad, D=dawk>> B A C<n><n>Input: Which choice best completes this sentence?:  ___ and ___ ____, you have ___ ____ each! Choices: <<A=hamburger, B=hot dog, C=sport, D=cool>> A = hamburger<n><n>Input: How do you solve this sum? The given string of digits must be expressed as the sum of distinct single-digit numerals: 19<n>Output: Start by looking at the first digit, and then take a second digit. You want to find any single-digit number on the left that is larger. If you look at the number 19, you see that the first digit 1, is greater than the second digit number 9. If you look at 29, you see that once again, the first digit, 2, is greater than the last digit, 9. And you keep doing this until you find a match. So the answer of the sum is 2+1+9 = 12<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the 5 free body diagram questions <n><n>#Instruction:Write a function for each body diagram, using the first image as an example.<n><n>Input: A function of a line must include the x and y values, while a function of a shape must include the x, y, and rot
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20. If Hurley is 14 years old, what are their combined ages 40 years from now?<n>Output: If Hurley is 14 years old, and the difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20, Richard is 20+14 = <<20+14=34>>34<n>Forty years from now, Hurley will be 14+40 = <<14+40=54>>54 years old.<n>Richard will be 40+34 = <<40+34=74>>74 years forty years from now.<n>Their combined ages forty years from now will be 74+54 = <<74+54=128>>128 years<n>So the final answer is 128<n><n>Input: Pablo’s mother agrees to pay him one cent for every page he reads. He plans to save the money for some candy. Pablo always checks out books that are exactly 150 pages. After reading his books, he went to the store and bought $15 worth of candy and had $3 leftover. How many books did Pablo read?<n>Output: He gets $1.5 per book because.01 x 150 = <<.01*150=1.5>>1.5<n>He earned $18 because 15 + 3 = <<15+3=18>>18<n>He read 12 books because 18 / 1.5 = <<18/1.5=12>>12<n>So the final answer is 12<n><n>Input: A group of six friends planned to buy a car. The cost of the car is $1700 and they plan to share the cost equally. They had a car wash to help raise funds, which would be taken out of the total cost. The remaining cost would be split between the six friends. At the car wash, they earn $500. However, Brad decided not to join in the purchase of the car. How much more does each friend have to pay now that Brad isn't participating?<n>Output: Start by finding the total that is left, $1700 car price - $500 earned at car wash = $<<1700-500=1200>>1200 remaining.<n>So the six friends should pay $1200 / 6 people = $<<1200/6=200>>200 each.<n>Since Brad is not joining, then the 5 friends have to split Brad's share which is $200/5 = $<<200/5=40>>40 each.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input: Harper needs to buy teacher appreciation gifts for her children’s teachers.  Her son has 3 different teachers and her daughter has 4.  If she spent $70 on gifts, how much did each gift cost?<n>Output: Her son has 3 teachers and her daughter has 4, so together they have 3+4 = <<3+4=7>>7 teachers<n>Harper has already spent $70 on 7 gifts, so she spent $70/7 = $<<70/7=10>>10 per gift<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input:If you're known to buy presents for others often you would be called what? Choices:  A: go shopping B: generous C: earn money D: have money E: gift buyer<n>Output:		 For a better word, use the letter C instead of 'gift buyer, choose 'generous'<n>So the final answer would be 'c'<n><n>Input: Alice has seven friends who each eat 3/7th of an apple. How much does Alice eat?<n>Output: Start with the number of people who ate: each person ate 3/7 so 7 people eat 3/7 each = <<7*3/7=21>>21<n>Alice eats what's left out of the total that the other 7 people ate: (21 - x) the total amount of 7 times 0.3 + x = <<(7*0.3+x)=24>>24 so that a+x=25-43=43 = <<43=25>>25<n>She ate that much.<n>So the final answered would be 25<n><n>Input:In a restaurant, customers are charged the same for every appetizer, entrée, and dessert. The total cost is equal to the number of appetizers multiplied by the number of entrées multiplied by the number desserts. The prices are as follows:<n><n>    Appetizers: $5<n><n>    Entrées: $10<n><n>    Desserts: $5<n><n>The total cost of the meal is $138.  How many appetizers were there?  Note: The answer is not 36<n>Output:<n>Start by looking at the amount of money it would take to pay the total.  $$6 \textrm{Appetizers} + 2 \textrm{Entrées} + 3 \textrm{Desserts} \textrm{cost }$$$  $$ = 35$$ The total amount of money to pay for all those three things is $$35 \textrm{ = dollars}$$ Since the total amount of money to spend on all the dishes is $$138$$ so we must multiply the amount of $$35$$ (total cost of everything) by $$3$$ (how many times) to get the number of appetizer $$. $ = 105$<n>Based on the formula where $ = 108 \ \textrm{Appetizer }$ So there were $$18$$ appetizers<n>So the final answer if

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20. If Hurley is 14 years old, what are their combined ages 40 years from now?<n>Output: If Hurley is 14 years old, and the difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20, Richard is 20+14 = <<20+14=34>>34<n>Forty years from now, Hurley will be 14+40 = <<14+40=54>>54 years old.<n>Richard will be 40+34 = <<40+34=74>>74 years forty years from now.<n>Their combined ages forty years from now will be 74+54 = <<74+54=128>>128 years<n>So the final answer is 128<n><n>Input: Pablo’s mother agrees to pay him one cent for every page he reads. He plans to save the money for some candy. Pablo always checks out books that are exactly 150 pages. After reading his books, he went to the store and bought $15 worth of candy and had $3 leftover. How many books did Pablo read?<n>Output: He gets $1.5 per book because.01 x 150 = <<.01*150=1.5>>1.5<n>He earned $18 because 15 + 3 = <<15+3=18>>18<n>He read 12 books because 18 / 1.5 = <<18/1.5=12>>12<n>So the final answer is 12<n><n>Input: A group of six friends planned to buy a car. The cost of the car is $1700 and they plan to share the cost equally. They had a car wash to help raise funds, which would be taken out of the total cost. The remaining cost would be split between the six friends. At the car wash, they earn $500. However, Brad decided not to join in the purchase of the car. How much more does each friend have to pay now that Brad isn't participating?<n>Output: Start by finding the total that is left, $1700 car price - $500 earned at car wash = $<<1700-500=1200>>1200 remaining.<n>So the six friends should pay $1200 / 6 people = $<<1200/6=200>>200 each.<n>Since Brad is not joining, then the 5 friends have to split Brad's share which is $200/5 = $<<200/5=40>>40 each.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input: Harper needs to buy teacher appreciation gifts for her children’s teachers.  Her son has 3 different teachers and her daughter has 4.  If she spent $70 on gifts, how much did each gift cost?<n>Output: Her son has 3 teachers and her daughter has 4, so together they have 3+4 = <<3+4=7>>7 teachers<n>Harper has already spent $70 on 7 gifts, so she spent $70/7 = $<<70/7=10>>10 per gift<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input:What place would a person go to look at zebras? Choices:  A: zoo B: museum C: hospital D: desk E: opera<n>Output:		They could go to the zoo because they said they went to a “place” that showed zebras. A is correct because there would be plenty of room to see zebras. They are mammals, after all. D is incorrect because they went to a place with zebras, not just a desk. Finally, C is wrong because the hospital does not show zebras.<n><n><n>Input:Anita plans to attend six events for her birthday. She wants to buy a 10-ticket lot from the city with the hope of getting to go to all the events. What is the chance that she will go to all six events?<n>Output:To go on every ticket the person must draw even numbered tickets, and the person must draw an odd number<n>This is because numbered tickets have 2 to 10 numbers: 2,4,6,8, 10<n>Odd numbers 1,3,5,7, 9<n>And all the odd numbers are in the ticket to go on the event, but all the even numbers are in the ticket not to go to the event.<n>So the chances she will go on each ticket is 2/10, 4/10, 6/10, and 8/10<n>The chances she will go to the event is 2/12 for the first one, and the chance she will go is 1/10

If Hurley is 14 years old, what are their combined ages 40 years from now?<n>Output: If Hurley is 14 years old, and the difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20, Richard is 20+14 = <<20+14=34>>34<n>Forty years from now, Hurley will be 14+40 = <<14+40=54>>54 years old.<n>Richard will be 40+34 = <<40+34=74>>74 years forty years from now.<n>Their combined ages forty years from now will be 74+54 = <<74+54=128>>128 years<n>So the final answer is 128<n><n>Input: Pablo’s mother agrees to pay him one cent for every page he reads. He plans to save the money for some candy. Pablo always checks out books that are exactly 150 pages. After reading his books, he went to the store and bought $15 worth of candy and had $3 leftover. How many books did Pablo read?<n>Output: He gets $1.5 per book because.01 x 150 = <<.01*150=1.5>>1.5<n>He earned $18 because 15 + 3 = <<15+3=18>>18<n>He read 12 books because 18 / 1.5 = <<18/1.5=12>>12<n>So the final answer is 12<n><n>Input: A group of six friends planned to buy a car. The cost of the car is $1700 and they plan to share the cost equally. They had a car wash to help raise funds, which would be taken out of the total cost. The remaining cost would be split between the six friends. At the car wash, they earn $500. However, Brad decided not to join in the purchase of the car. How much more does each friend have to pay now that Brad isn't participating?<n>Output: Start by finding the total that is left, $1700 car price - $500 earned at car wash = $<<1700-500=1200>>1200 remaining.<n>So the six friends should pay $1200 / 6 people = $<<1200/6=200>>200 each.<n>Since Brad is not joining, then the 5 friends have to split Brad's share which is $200/5 = $<<200/5=40>>40 each.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input: Harper needs to buy teacher appreciation gifts for her children’s teachers.  Her son has 3 different teachers and her daughter has 4.  If she spent $70 on gifts, how much did each gift cost?<n>Output: Her son has 3 teachers and her daughter has 4, so together they have 3+4 = <<3+4=7>>7 teachers<n>Harper has already spent $70 on 7 gifts, so she spent $70/7 = $<<70/7=10>>10 per gift<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input:Remembering past successe is likely to cause what? Choices:  A: problems B: crying C: inspiration D: trauma E: nightmares<n>Output:		E. Nightmares<n>Remembering past successes is likely to cause nightmares because remembering successes is a negative emotion. Remembering the great times is likely to cause night terrors and dreams about your failure.<n><n>Input:The population of a town is growing at a steady and predictable rate. After 4 years, the population will be 41% larger than it is today. What is the current population of the town?<n>Output: To answer this question: Let C represent the current population. P/4 is the growing rate.<n>P/4 * 4= C new value<n>If C is the current population, then the P/4 will be C x 4<n>So P/4 * 4 = C * 4 = <<4C>>C*4<n>So the final answer to find the current population is C<n><n>Input: What is 10 times 5?<n>Input: The difference between two numbers is 23. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20. If Hurley is 14 years old, what are their combined ages 40 years from now?<n>Output: If Hurley is 14 years old, and the difference in ages between Richard and Hurley is 20, Richard is 20+14 = <<20+14=34>>34<n>Forty years from now, Hurley will be 14+40 = <<14+40=54>>54 years old.<n>Richard will be 40+34 = <<40+34=74>>74 years forty years from now.<n>Their combined ages forty years from now will be 74+54 = <<74+54=128>>128 years<n>So the final answer is 128<n><n>Input: Pablo’s mother agrees to pay him one cent for every page he reads. Choices:  A: zoo B: workplace C: sky D: new york city E: many places<n>Output:		Choice D is the only option where you can see animals<n>It is only listed, so we have it = <<it=A>>A<n>It is not listed, so we don't have it = <<it!=B>>B<n>It is listed in D, so we will list it = <<it=E>>E<n>It is not listed and therefore not in E, so we will not list it = <<it!=F>>F<n>It is in D but not listed = <<it=C>>C<n>The only options where we can see animals are A, B, C, D and E<n>The remaining options are not listed, so those have to be ignored<n>The only options where an animal is visible are the ones in D (A, B, C and E)<n>The final answer is D<n><n>Input: What was the sum of all the ages in 1999?<n>Option A: 76<n>Option B: 838<n>Option C: 1034<n>Option D: 1093<n><n>Output: There is only 1 9 in the year, so it is not the year that follows 8<n>There was only 8 in the year, so the next year is 8+1<n>1999 is not listed, so 19 is not listed either<n>76 is listed, so 1000-76 is not listed<n>76 is listed in 1993, so 1993-76 is not the next year<n>76+1 is listed in 1822, so 1821-19 is not the next year either<n>76+3 = 79 -1 is not listed, nor is the next year 80<n>76+5=81 is not listed<n>736 = 1822 is not listed either<n>1128 = 1823 is not listed<n>1199 = 1824 is not listed<n>6111 = 1825 is not the next year, nor is 8280<n>30451 = 1943 is not in the year before 1824<n>41144 = 1860 is not in the year 1861<n>102960 = 190
